SOS Biologiacal data visualisation: CORTISOL

#load libraries: library(dplyr) library(tidyverse) library(ggplot2) library(data.table) library(stringr) library(plyr) library(ggpubr) library(DescTools) library(MESS)

First, we import the SOS_hormones_cleaned.csv file and remove participants who do not have Cortisol data at all 4 time points.

#import cleaned bioloigcal dataset:
setwd("~/Documents/8_Byrne_work/SOS_Bioloigical_data_cleaned")
SOS_hormones_cleaned <- read.csv('SOS_hormones_cleaned.csv')
SOS_hormones_cleaned$SampleID <- as.character(SOS_hormones_cleaned$SampleID)

#Create variable specfic to Cortisol:
SOS_Cortisol <- SOS_hormones_cleaned[,c("SampleID", "Time","Cortisol_ug_dL", "Cortisol_log", "Cortisol_log")]

#Remove participants who do not have all 3 timepoints:
SOS_Cortisol_T1 = SOS_Cortisol %>% filter(Time == "1")
SOS_Cortisol_T2 = SOS_Cortisol %>% filter(Time == "2")
SOS_Cortisol_T3 = SOS_Cortisol %>% filter(Time == "3")
SOS_Cortisol_T4 = SOS_Cortisol %>% filter(Time == "4")

Merge1 <-merge(SOS_Cortisol_T1, SOS_Cortisol_T2, by = "SampleID", all = FALSE, all.x = TRUE)
Merge2 <-merge(Merge1, SOS_Cortisol_T3, by = "SampleID", all = FALSE, all.x = TRUE)
SOS_Cortisol_reshaped <-merge(Merge2, SOS_Cortisol_T4, by = "SampleID", all = FALSE, all.x = TRUE)
column names Time.x, Cortisol_ug_dL.x, Cortisol_log.x, Cortisol_log.1.x, Time.y, Cortisol_ug_dL.y, Cortisol_log.y, Cortisol_log.1.y are duplicated in the result
SOS_Cortisol_all_timepoints <- na.omit(SOS_Cortisol_reshaped)

#Merge to now include only the people who have all 4 timepoints:
SOS_Cortisol_final <- merge(SOS_Cortisol, SOS_Cortisol_all_timepoints, by = "SampleID", all = FALSE)
SOS_Cortisol_final <- SOS_Cortisol_final[1:5]
SOS_Cortisol_final <- (SOS_Cortisol_final %>% arrange(SampleID,Time))

total <- unique(SOS_Cortisol$SampleID)
total_keep <- unique(SOS_Cortisol_final$SampleID)
perc_all_timepoints <- ((length(total_keep))/(length(total)))*100

# Identify where the maximum value is (T1-T4) and add as a variable to dataframe
PeakTime <- list()
PeakTime_id <- list()
Responders <- list()

for (i in unique(SOS_Cortisol_final$SampleID)) {
    idx <- which(SOS_Cortisol_final$SampleID==i, arr.ind=TRUE)
    #Get participants peak timepoint
    PeakTime[i] <- which.max(SOS_Cortisol_final$Cortisol_log[idx])
    #Get SampleID
    PeakTime_id[i] <- i
    #Using T1 > T2,T3,T4 as exclusion criteria, split group into "Responders" and "Not Responders"
      if (PeakTime[i] == "1"){ 
      Responders[i] <- "0"
      } else {
      Responders[i] <- "1"
      }
    }

PeakTime <- data.frame(PeakTime)
PeakTime <- t(PeakTime)
PeakTime <- data.frame(PeakTime)

PeakTime_id <- data.frame(PeakTime_id)
PeakTime_id <- t(PeakTime_id)
PeakTime_id <- data.frame(PeakTime_id)

Responders <- data.frame(Responders)
Responders <- t(Responders)
Responders <- data.frame(Responders)


Peak_time_all <- cbind(PeakTime, PeakTime_id, Responders)
#Clear variables no longer needed:
rm(PeakTime, PeakTime_id)

names(Peak_time_all)[1]<- "PeakTime"

rm(Peak_time_all)

Some participants may be non responders, meaning they did not show a response to the task. If their peak response was at Timepoint 1, we have classified participants as non responders (0). All other participants (who show peaks at Timepoints 2,3 or 4) are included as responders (1).

#Clear variables no longer needed:

We want to know whether responders (1) and non-responders (0) showed a significantly different response at Timepoint 1:

#Do a t-test to compare whether non-responders(0) had a higher T1 than responders(1)
Time_point_1 <- SOS_Cortisol_final[1:7]
Time_point_1 = Time_point_1 %>% filter(Time == "1")

compare_means(Cortisol_log ~ Responders, data = Time_point_1,
              method = "t.test")

People show differing baseline levels of cortisol responding. We can calculate their relative change from baseline (Timepoint 1) at Timepoints 2,3 and 4.

rm(i, idx)

#For each subject, normalise time points 2,3 and 4, to timepoint 1.
Normalised_values <- list()
Normalise_id <- list()

for (i in as.character(SOS_Cortisol_final$SampleID)) {
  idx <- which(SOS_Cortisol_final$SampleID==i, arr.ind=TRUE)
  SampleID_current <- i
  baseline <- SOS_Cortisol_final$Cortisol_log[idx[1]]
    for (t in 1:4){
    Normalised_values[idx[t]] <- (SOS_Cortisol_final$Cortisol_log[idx[t]] - baseline)
    Normalise_id[idx[t]] <- SampleID_current 
    }
}

#Reformat lists into data.frames     
Normalised_values <- data.frame(Normalised_values)
Normalised_values <- t(Normalised_values)
Normalised_values <- data.frame(Normalised_values)

Normalise_id <- data.frame(Normalise_id)
Normalise_id <- t(Normalise_id)
Normalise_id <- data.frame(Normalise_id)
#Merge two data.frames
Normalised_all <- cbind(Normalised_values, Normalise_id)

#Clear variables no longer needed:
rm(Normalised_values, Normalise_id)

#Rename columns for merge (SampleID, also helps for checking that the rows have matched appropriately)
names(Normalised_all)[1]<- "BL_Norm_Cortisol_log"
names(Normalised_all)[2]<- "SampleID"

#Merge with SOS_Cortisol_final and remove unecessary extra SampleID column:
SOS_Cortisol_final <- cbind(SOS_Cortisol_final, Normalised_all)
SOS_Cortisol_final <- SOS_Cortisol_final[1:8]

#Clear variables no longer needed:
rm(Normalised_all, baseline, i, idx, SampleID_current, t)

#Calculate the area under the curve for each responder: 
AUC_list <- list()
AUC_id <- list()

for (i in unique(SOS_Cortisol_final$SampleID)) {
    idx <- which(SOS_Cortisol_final$SampleID==i, arr.ind=TRUE)
    #Get participants AUC for T1-4:
    AUC_list[i] <- auc(
                SOS_Cortisol_final$Time[idx],
                SOS_Cortisol_final$BL_Norm_Cortisol_log[idx],
                from = min(1, na.rm = TRUE),
                to = max(4, na.rm = TRUE),
                type = c("spline"),
                absolutearea = FALSE,
                subdivisions = 100
                )
    #Get SampleID
    AUC_id[i] <- i
}
#Reformat lists into data.frames     
AUC_list <- data.frame(AUC_list)
AUC_list <- t(AUC_list)
AUC_list <- data.frame(AUC_list)

AUC_id <- data.frame(AUC_id)
AUC_id <- t(AUC_id)
AUC_id <- data.frame(AUC_id)

#Merge two data.frames
AUC_all <- cbind(AUC_list, AUC_id)

#Clear variables no longer needed:
rm(AUC_list, AUC_id)

#Rename columns for merge (SampleID, also helps for checking that the rows have matched appropriately)
names(AUC_all)[1]<- "AUC_BL_Norm_Cortisol_log"
names(AUC_all)[2]<- "SampleID"

#Merge with SOS_Cortisol_final and remove unecessary extra SampleID column:
SOS_Cortisol_final <-merge(SOS_Cortisol_final, AUC_all, by = "SampleID", all = TRUE)

We can see that the greatest change in Cortisol level occurs between T2 and T3. We are therefore interested to quantify the magnitude of this change per participant. If participants change is +ve (meaning an increase from T2 > T3) = 1. If participants change is -ve (meaning a decrease from T2 > T3) = 0:

T2T3_list <- list()
T2T3_id <- list()
T2T3_direction <- list()

for (i in as.character(SOS_Cortisol_final$SampleID)){
    idx <- which(SOS_Cortisol_final$SampleID==i, arr.ind=TRUE)
    T2T3_id[i] <-i
    T2T3_list[i] <-(SOS_Cortisol_final$Cortisol_log[idx[3]] - SOS_Cortisol_final$Cortisol_log[idx[2]])
     if (T2T3_list[i] > "0"){ 
      T2T3_direction[i] <- "1"
      } else {
      T2T3_direction[i] <- "0"
      }
    }

#Reformat lists into data.frames     
T2T3_list <- data.frame(T2T3_list)
T2T3_list <- t(T2T3_list)
T2T3_list <- data.frame(T2T3_list)

T2T3_id <- data.frame(T2T3_id)
T2T3_id <- t(T2T3_id)
T2T3_id <- data.frame(T2T3_id)

T2T3_direction <- data.frame(T2T3_direction)
T2T3_direction <- t(T2T3_direction)
T2T3_direction <- data.frame(T2T3_direction)

#Merge two data.frames
T2T3_all <- cbind(T2T3_list, T2T3_id, T2T3_direction)

#Clear variables no longer needed:
rm(T2T3_list, T2T3_id, T2T3_direction)

#Rename columns for merge (SampleID, also helps for checking that the rows have matched appropriately)
